      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While free speech is a foundational value, the concept of absolute freedom is philosophically debated; most systems allow for limitations, such as defamation or incitement to violence. A compelling counter-argument is the \"harm principle,\" which posits that speech can be restricted when it directly and demonstrably causes tangible harm to others. Acknowledging this complexity allows you to argue that the *intent* of regulation—from curbing actual violence to mere narrative control—is what determines whether it becomes authoritarian.",
